00:00:23.100 --> 00:00:25.350
IAIN STEWART: All right,
that's roughly where we were.

00:00:25.350 --> 00:00:28.530
So last time, we started
talking about SCET.

00:00:28.530 --> 00:00:30.480
We said it's going
to be a theory that

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:34.100
can describe energetic
hadrons and energetic jets.

00:00:34.100 --> 00:00:37.080
Our first example was
discussing about a process

00:00:37.080 --> 00:00:40.560
with an energetic hadron,
which is this pink pion.

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:44.540
So the pion has a large
momentum, large energy.

00:00:44.540 --> 00:00:45.990
It's much bigger
than lambda QCD.

00:00:45.990 --> 00:00:47.400
It's much bigger than in m pi.

00:00:47.400 --> 00:00:50.470
And it moves basically along
a light cone direction.

00:00:50.470 --> 00:00:53.560
So that was a motivation for us
to use light cone coordinates.

00:00:53.560 --> 00:00:56.010
So we introduce
an n and an n bar.

00:00:56.010 --> 00:01:02.550
And with that n and n bar,
which satisfy n squared 0,

00:01:02.550 --> 00:01:08.520
n bar squared 0, and n dot n
bar equals 2 as a normalization

00:01:08.520 --> 00:01:11.752
convention, we can
decompose any momentum P

00:01:11.752 --> 00:01:16.380
mu in terms of components along
n, components along n bar,

00:01:16.380 --> 00:01:18.630
and then the remaining two
components which we call

00:01:18.630 --> 00:01:22.450
the perpendicular components.

00:01:22.450 --> 00:01:27.224
So we can also write the metric
out in these coordinates.

00:01:32.164 --> 00:01:34.500
And this kind of makes
explicit that you

00:01:34.500 --> 00:01:36.570
have this off-diagonal
nature to the basis,

00:01:36.570 --> 00:01:38.830
that you have n
mu with n bar mu.

00:01:46.500 --> 00:01:49.020
So unlike Cartesian
coordinates, where

00:01:49.020 --> 00:01:50.880
the component along
a direction is just

00:01:50.880 --> 00:01:53.850
given by dotting that
vector into the vector

00:01:53.850 --> 00:01:56.640
you start with, here
the component along n

00:01:56.640 --> 00:01:59.603
is given by dotting n
bar into the vector.

00:01:59.603 --> 00:02:01.770
And that's reflected in the
metric here in the sense

00:02:01.770 --> 00:02:04.320
that you have these
terms n within n bar.

00:02:08.160 --> 00:02:12.060
So you can do this with any
tensor if you have an epsilon.

00:02:12.060 --> 00:02:16.290
You can find an epsilon
perp tensor, for example,

00:02:16.290 --> 00:02:24.180
by taking epsilon and
putting in an n bar and an n.

00:02:24.180 --> 00:02:26.070
And then this would be
a two-component tensor

00:02:26.070 --> 00:02:27.960
that behaves in the
perpendicular direction

00:02:27.960 --> 00:02:30.060
as an antisymmetric tensor.

00:02:30.060 --> 00:02:33.570
And this g perp mu nu
would be effectively living

00:02:33.570 --> 00:02:37.470
in the little subspace
of the perp coordinates.

00:02:37.470 --> 00:02:39.490
And again, it's a
metric tensor there.

00:02:39.490 --> 00:02:43.440
And this would be the
antisymmetric tensor there.

00:02:43.440 --> 00:02:46.710
OK, so these are the
coordinates we're going to use.

00:02:53.610 --> 00:02:56.990
So n here had a
physical motivation,

00:02:56.990 --> 00:02:59.150
as you saw from my picture.

00:02:59.150 --> 00:03:01.280
The pion was moving
in the n direction.

00:03:01.280 --> 00:03:03.350
And bar was just
a vector that we

00:03:03.350 --> 00:03:05.600
decided that we needed in
order to define things.

00:03:08.760 --> 00:03:11.540
So if you have some vector
where n squared is 0

00:03:11.540 --> 00:03:14.360
and you want to make a
decomposition of coordinates,

00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:15.770
then you're required
to introduce

00:03:15.770 --> 00:03:26.110
a complimentary vector,
which is this n bar

00:03:26.110 --> 00:03:31.570
to make the decomposition
for the reasons I said.

00:03:38.123 --> 00:03:39.790
The simplest choice
that you could make,

00:03:39.790 --> 00:03:46.540
if you made this choice
for n, so if we choose n

00:03:46.540 --> 00:03:58.990
to be 1, 0, 0,
minus 1, as I did,

00:03:58.990 --> 00:04:03.260
then the simplest thing you
could do for n bar is to pick n

00:04:03.260 --> 00:04:07.616
bar to be 1, 0, 0, plus 1.

00:04:07.616 --> 00:04:10.600
So then that would be
a lightlike vector.

00:04:10.600 --> 00:04:13.660
When you dot it into
this vector, you get 2.

00:04:13.660 --> 00:04:19.459
And it satisfies all the
criteria that we would need.

00:04:19.459 --> 00:04:21.709
If I choose these
two vectors, then I

00:04:21.709 --> 00:04:23.420
have to find what
perp is because perp

00:04:23.420 --> 00:04:26.030
is the space that's
orthogonal to these vectors.

00:04:26.030 --> 00:04:31.490
So that's these two
coordinates, OK?

00:04:31.490 --> 00:04:36.440
So perp in general is defined
such that n dot P perp is 0

00:04:36.440 --> 00:04:40.040
and n bar dot P perp is 0.

00:04:40.040 --> 00:04:41.540
It's the orthogonal
two directions

00:04:41.540 --> 00:04:44.642
to the ones that are
picked out by an n bar.

00:04:44.642 --> 00:04:46.850
And so you need to know what
n and n bar are in order

00:04:46.850 --> 00:04:47.808
to define what perp is.

00:04:50.550 --> 00:04:51.620
So this is one choice.

00:04:51.620 --> 00:04:54.140
You could make other choices.

00:04:54.140 --> 00:04:57.330
And we'll come back
to this later on.

00:04:57.330 --> 00:05:04.910
So just by way of example, if
I have the same choice for n,

00:05:04.910 --> 00:05:11.210
but I choose n bar
to be 3, 2, 2, 1,

00:05:11.210 --> 00:05:13.790
that would also be a
choice that's equally good.

00:05:18.130 --> 00:05:19.360
I need this to be minus 1.

00:05:26.944 --> 00:05:31.420
I'll do this, make
my choice work.

00:05:31.420 --> 00:05:34.180
I guess, well, OK, if
we want the same sign,

00:05:34.180 --> 00:05:35.200
then I have to do this.

00:05:39.910 --> 00:05:42.820
OK, so 9 minus 8, this
thing still squares to 0.

00:05:42.820 --> 00:05:47.740
You dot it, you get
3 minus 1 is 2, OK?

00:05:47.740 --> 00:05:50.320
So it still satisfies the
criteria that we had here.

00:05:53.440 --> 00:05:56.360
And it points in some
other weird direction.

00:05:56.360 --> 00:05:58.480
So the point is that this
is an auxiliary vector,

00:05:58.480 --> 00:06:03.585
and there's some freedom
in what you pick for it.

00:06:03.585 --> 00:06:05.710
And once you've picked
this, if you pick these two,

00:06:05.710 --> 00:06:08.230
you would have a different
definition of perp.

00:06:08.230 --> 00:06:08.740
OK.

00:06:08.740 --> 00:06:12.250
But it's an equally
valid possible choice.

00:06:12.250 --> 00:06:14.840
And we'll actually exploit
this freedom later on.

00:06:14.840 --> 00:06:18.430
But for now, we'll mostly focus
on picking the simplest choice.

00:06:21.150 --> 00:06:23.610
OK, what we're actually
interested in describing

00:06:23.610 --> 00:06:26.310
in these processes
is not just the plan,

00:06:26.310 --> 00:06:27.870
but what goes on
inside the plan.

00:06:27.870 --> 00:06:30.730
What is the quark level process?

00:06:30.730 --> 00:06:34.050
So we're interested
in the constituents.

00:06:34.050 --> 00:06:35.430
That's where the dynamics are.

00:06:43.522 --> 00:06:46.548
Is there any questions
before I keep going?

00:06:46.548 --> 00:06:48.840
No.

00:06:48.840 --> 00:06:52.710
So in this process, B to D
pi, if you think about it

00:06:52.710 --> 00:06:54.100
in the rest frame
of the B meson,

00:06:54.100 --> 00:06:56.168
which is the most natural
frame, then the B meson

00:06:56.168 --> 00:06:57.960
we've already learned
how to describe that.

00:06:57.960 --> 00:07:03.900
We can describe that with
HQET, same with the D meson.

00:07:03.900 --> 00:07:06.390
And we know that the things
that are inside the B and the D

00:07:06.390 --> 00:07:10.930
meson are one heavy quark and
then a bunch of soft stuff.

00:07:10.930 --> 00:07:13.945
So I'll call these guys soft
because the dynamical part is

00:07:13.945 --> 00:07:14.445
soft.

00:07:23.600 --> 00:07:33.720
And so we can use HQET
for them as we did before.

00:07:43.930 --> 00:07:47.590
And that means we're describing
gluons and quarks that

00:07:47.590 --> 00:07:54.205
are inside these hadrons
where the forward momentum are

00:07:54.205 --> 00:07:57.370
of order lambda QCD.

00:07:57.370 --> 00:08:00.280
The pion, on the other hand,
is what we would collinear.

00:08:16.620 --> 00:08:18.590
So as I already described,
the pion's energy

00:08:18.590 --> 00:08:21.060
is much greater than its mass.

00:08:21.060 --> 00:08:21.905
Its highly boosted.

00:08:29.720 --> 00:08:32.600
If you were to talk about
it in the rest frame,

00:08:32.600 --> 00:08:34.880
then like the B and the D
meson, then the constituents

00:08:34.880 --> 00:08:40.215
of the pion would have
momentum of order lambda QCD.

00:08:40.215 --> 00:08:42.590
But if you were to talk about
the pion in the rest frame,

00:08:42.590 --> 00:08:47.050
you'd have to talk about the B
and the D in the boosted frame.

00:08:47.050 --> 00:08:49.150
So let's stick with
describing the B and the D

00:08:49.150 --> 00:08:52.790
in the rest frame or
close to the rest frame.

00:08:52.790 --> 00:08:55.150
The B meson is in
its rest frame.

00:08:55.150 --> 00:08:57.610
In the D meson is slow.

00:08:57.610 --> 00:09:00.700
And in that case, we're stuck
with the pion being energetic.

00:09:03.820 --> 00:09:12.640
So in rest frame,
our pion would be--

00:09:17.890 --> 00:09:25.698
it would also have
quarks and gluons

00:09:25.698 --> 00:09:27.560
our P mu is order lambda QCD.

00:09:32.780 --> 00:09:35.360
And we can actually just take
that result, once we know that,

00:09:35.360 --> 00:09:38.720
and boost it to another frame.

00:09:38.720 --> 00:09:43.520
So let's just boost along
z hat by some kappa that's

00:09:43.520 --> 00:09:46.695
much greater than
1 as the boost.

00:09:46.695 --> 00:09:48.570
And the way that light
cone coordinates boost

00:09:48.570 --> 00:09:49.290
is very simple.

00:09:49.290 --> 00:09:52.040
If you're along the axis of
the light cone coordinates,

00:09:52.040 --> 00:09:55.410
it's multiplicative.

00:09:55.410 --> 00:09:57.500
So P minus gets
enhanced by some amount.

00:09:57.500 --> 00:09:59.390
P plus gets suppressed
by the same amount.

00:10:02.100 --> 00:10:05.268
That's one nice thing
about these coordinates.

00:10:05.268 --> 00:10:07.310
And of course, P perp
doesn't change because it's

00:10:07.310 --> 00:10:08.510
perpendicular to the boost.

00:10:11.570 --> 00:10:14.925
So now, we can get our
pion, which is moving,

00:10:14.925 --> 00:10:15.800
which should be pink.

00:10:25.340 --> 00:10:27.020
And if we ask about
its constituents,

00:10:27.020 --> 00:10:29.060
we just boost the components
of this for vector.

00:10:38.430 --> 00:10:41.330
So we ask about how they scale.

00:10:41.330 --> 00:10:44.810
And we look at the
different components.

00:10:44.810 --> 00:10:47.870
The plus, minus, and perp
scale differently now,

00:10:47.870 --> 00:10:50.320
so we have to break
it up by that.

00:10:50.320 --> 00:10:53.240
And if we boost it by
this amount Q or lambda

00:10:53.240 --> 00:11:02.970
over Q, Q over
lambda, then that's

00:11:02.970 --> 00:11:06.440
the scaling for
this boosted pion.

00:11:06.440 --> 00:11:06.940
OK.

00:11:06.940 --> 00:11:10.110
So now, it's got a component
in the minus direction.

00:11:10.110 --> 00:11:13.650
n bar dot P is
order Q. That's what

00:11:13.650 --> 00:11:15.360
we saw before when
we decomposed the P,

00:11:15.360 --> 00:11:18.570
that it was basically Q
times a lightlike vector.

00:11:18.570 --> 00:11:20.430
But that was the pion.

00:11:20.430 --> 00:11:23.130
Now, we're talking about the
constituents inside the pion.

00:11:23.130 --> 00:11:25.638
Constituents inside
the pion fill it out.

00:11:25.638 --> 00:11:27.180
They fill it out in
the perpendicular

00:11:27.180 --> 00:11:30.210
by an amount lambda QCD that's
perpendicular to the direction

00:11:30.210 --> 00:11:31.350
of its motion.

00:11:31.350 --> 00:11:34.440
And then the plus momentum
got correspondingly smaller

00:11:34.440 --> 00:11:37.310
as the minus momentum
have got bigger,

00:11:37.310 --> 00:11:38.310
so we have that scaling.

00:11:40.830 --> 00:11:42.510
And so the relative
scaling here is

00:11:42.510 --> 00:11:45.110
what actually defines
something being collinear.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:53.610
So the relative
scaling of this vector

00:11:53.610 --> 00:11:58.230
here is that the P minus is
much bigger than the P perp is

00:11:58.230 --> 00:12:00.480
much bigger than the P plus.

00:12:00.480 --> 00:12:02.472
And that's what we
mean by collinear.

00:12:06.900 --> 00:12:08.490
It's collimated
in some direction,

00:12:08.490 --> 00:12:09.990
and that direction
is the direction

00:12:09.990 --> 00:12:10.907
of the large momentum.

00:12:13.353 --> 00:12:14.770
You always have
to be careful when

00:12:14.770 --> 00:12:16.810
you say things like that
because the component

00:12:16.810 --> 00:12:19.610
along the direction is the
opposite lightlike vector,

00:12:19.610 --> 00:12:22.600
but I think you'll
always know what I mean.

00:12:22.600 --> 00:12:27.730
OK, so in the n mu direction, we
have a large component P minus.

00:12:27.730 --> 00:12:29.837
And that defines this
thing is collimated

00:12:29.837 --> 00:12:30.920
in a particular direction.

00:12:30.920 --> 00:12:34.065
It's perpendicular fluctuations
to that direction are small.

00:12:34.065 --> 00:12:35.440
And so all the
degrees of freedom

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:40.330
that are in this boosted pion
have that type of scaling.

00:12:40.330 --> 00:12:42.070
So what we're
describing, or what

00:12:42.070 --> 00:12:45.370
we want to describe if we
have a field theory for this,

00:12:45.370 --> 00:12:47.110
is we want to
describe, if you like,

00:12:47.110 --> 00:12:57.340
fluctuations about the
pion momentum, which,

00:12:57.340 --> 00:13:06.580
ignoring the pion mass, we could
just take it to be like this.

00:13:06.580 --> 00:13:09.700
And the size of the
fluctuations we need to treat

00:13:09.700 --> 00:13:12.250
are things that can fluctuate
by amounts of this size.

00:13:16.110 --> 00:13:17.610
So the field theory
is going to have

00:13:17.610 --> 00:13:23.153
to describe fluctuations about
some kind of canonical scaling.

00:13:23.153 --> 00:13:24.570
And the field
theory for this pion

00:13:24.570 --> 00:13:26.520
is going to have
to be describing

00:13:26.520 --> 00:13:29.100
collinear fluctuations
that are of this type.

00:13:29.100 --> 00:13:33.560
Just like the HQET had to
describe soft fluctuations,

00:13:33.560 --> 00:13:36.690
P mu's of order lambda QCD
ignorant of the heavy quark

00:13:36.690 --> 00:13:40.730
mass, here it's a little
bit more complicated.

00:13:40.730 --> 00:13:43.230
But that's the kind of thing
we want the field theory to do.

00:13:47.300 --> 00:13:48.520
Any questions about that?

00:13:57.220 --> 00:14:02.340
So the way that we write this
is we say that P plus, P minus,

00:14:02.340 --> 00:14:08.460
P perp has a particular
scaling that we

00:14:08.460 --> 00:14:13.200
call lambda squared
1 lambda where

00:14:13.200 --> 00:14:14.640
lambda is some small parameter.

00:14:20.510 --> 00:14:22.750
And if we have a momentum
that scales that way,

00:14:22.750 --> 00:14:24.066
we call it collinear.

00:14:35.320 --> 00:14:39.630
So this is generic any
case with any lambda.

00:14:39.630 --> 00:14:43.116
And our allowed here was
just lambda QCD over Q.

00:14:43.116 --> 00:14:46.680
But if we encounter
another physical problem

00:14:46.680 --> 00:14:49.620
where the lambda
was different, we

00:14:49.620 --> 00:14:51.224
would also call that collinear.

00:14:55.870 --> 00:15:00.970
All right, so what's a
nice way of picturing this,

00:15:00.970 --> 00:15:02.980
what we're doing here?

00:15:02.980 --> 00:15:04.990
Because it's a little
bit different than you're

00:15:04.990 --> 00:15:07.223
used to with an
effective field theory.

00:15:07.223 --> 00:15:09.640
Usually, with an effective
field theory, what you're doing

00:15:09.640 --> 00:15:12.593
is you're separating modes
by their invariant mass.

00:15:12.593 --> 00:15:15.010
You have things with large
invariant mass, small invariant

00:15:15.010 --> 00:15:16.618
mass.

00:15:16.618 --> 00:15:18.160
If you think about
massive particles,

00:15:18.160 --> 00:15:20.950
well, that's just the
invariant mass squared.

00:15:20.950 --> 00:15:22.900
So if you're separating
massive particles

00:15:22.900 --> 00:15:25.780
from massless particles
or less massive particles,

00:15:25.780 --> 00:15:30.370
you're really separating things
along an invariant mass curve.

00:15:30.370 --> 00:15:33.940
Just an invariant mass variable
is used for the separation.

00:15:33.940 --> 00:15:35.740
And that doesn't
quite suffice here.

00:15:35.740 --> 00:15:38.830
Because as you saw, the pion
in the B and the D meson,

00:15:38.830 --> 00:15:41.620
they both had P squared
of order lambda QCD.

00:15:41.620 --> 00:15:44.710
What separates the pion
from the B or the D meson

00:15:44.710 --> 00:15:47.350
is this morphyne structure.

00:16:05.290 --> 00:16:07.720
So SCET is actually an
example of an effective field

00:16:07.720 --> 00:16:12.340
theory that requires at
least more than one variable

00:16:12.340 --> 00:16:14.830
to describe where the
degrees of freedom live.

00:16:19.413 --> 00:16:21.580
So we can draw a picture
for what we've been talking

00:16:21.580 --> 00:16:24.880
about here in two variables.

00:16:24.880 --> 00:16:26.470
Let's just pick P
minus and P plus.

00:16:31.600 --> 00:16:35.980
And essentially, what's
going on in this space is

00:16:35.980 --> 00:16:38.260
you can think that there's
degrees of freedom that

00:16:38.260 --> 00:16:40.840
live in this space at
different locations.

00:16:47.820 --> 00:16:51.570
So out here, if I draw
a hyperbola like this,

00:16:51.570 --> 00:16:58.938
then remember that P squared
was P plus times P minus minus P

00:16:58.938 --> 00:16:59.480
perp squared.

00:16:59.480 --> 00:17:02.460
But let's ignore P perp
squared for this picture.

00:17:02.460 --> 00:17:05.839
So if I draw a curve of constant
P squared in this plane, then

00:17:05.839 --> 00:17:07.010
it's I hyperbola.

00:17:07.010 --> 00:17:08.930
So these are curves
of constant P squared.

00:17:16.540 --> 00:17:18.670
And this one here has
P squared of order Q

00:17:18.670 --> 00:17:21.800
squared, which might be Mb
squared or some hard scale.

00:17:21.800 --> 00:17:25.420
So this any degrees of freedom
that live on this curve,

00:17:25.420 --> 00:17:27.640
or in particularly
these ones, would

00:17:27.640 --> 00:17:29.752
be what we would call
hard degrees of freedom.

00:17:29.752 --> 00:17:31.960
And those are something that
we want to integrate out

00:17:31.960 --> 00:17:34.210
of the effective theory.

00:17:34.210 --> 00:17:37.180
And the other degrees of freedom
that we've been talking about

00:17:37.180 --> 00:17:38.680
have smaller invariant mass.

00:17:38.680 --> 00:17:42.460
So this hyperbola down here
has P squared of order lambda

00:17:42.460 --> 00:17:44.410
QCD squared.

00:17:44.410 --> 00:17:46.570
But there's two different
degrees of freedom

00:17:46.570 --> 00:17:48.340
that live on this curve.

00:17:48.340 --> 00:17:50.020
One of them has a large P minus.

00:17:50.020 --> 00:17:53.110
That's the collinear one,
so it should be pink.

00:18:02.030 --> 00:18:08.090
And then the soft
one lives down there.

00:18:08.090 --> 00:18:12.680
So P minus here is scaling,
if you like, lambda to the 0.

00:18:12.680 --> 00:18:17.135
And here, for this soft mode,
which also exists in this case,

00:18:17.135 --> 00:18:18.635
this is actually
going to be lambda.

00:18:24.060 --> 00:18:27.210
So you can contrast
that type of picture

00:18:27.210 --> 00:18:31.260
with a more usual picture where
you would just have one line.

00:18:31.260 --> 00:18:32.940
And you'd say there's
some modes up here

00:18:32.940 --> 00:18:33.900
and some modes down there.

00:18:33.900 --> 00:18:35.400
And you'd integrate
out these modes.

00:18:35.400 --> 00:18:36.790
And you keep those modes.

00:18:36.790 --> 00:18:38.582
This is a little
different because you want

00:18:38.582 --> 00:18:39.798
to integrate out these modes.

00:18:39.798 --> 00:18:41.340
You want to keep
both of those modes,

00:18:41.340 --> 00:18:43.465
but they live in a little
bit of a different place.

00:18:43.465 --> 00:18:45.960
And that's actually going to
be important to formulating

00:18:45.960 --> 00:18:47.760
the effective theory.

00:18:47.760 --> 00:18:50.910
So the way that you should think
about this, physically the way

00:18:50.910 --> 00:18:53.490
you should think about it, is
that these modes are kind of

00:18:53.490 --> 00:18:54.840
localized in that region.

00:18:57.360 --> 00:19:05.320
This is the right
physical picture,

00:19:05.320 --> 00:19:08.440
which requires another variable
besides just invariant mass

00:19:08.440 --> 00:19:15.940
in order to specify that, right?

00:19:15.940 --> 00:19:18.790
The reason we don't have to draw
a third direction for P perp

00:19:18.790 --> 00:19:25.410
is because it was just
redundant information.

00:19:25.410 --> 00:19:28.455
P perp squared is
always of P plus P

00:19:28.455 --> 00:19:30.330
minus if you're talking
about fluctuations

00:19:30.330 --> 00:19:31.538
that are near the mass shell.

00:19:40.490 --> 00:19:43.400
For a massless mode, that mass
shell is P squared equals 0.

00:19:47.030 --> 00:19:49.730
And so P perp would just be
providing redundant information

00:19:49.730 --> 00:19:51.605
to our picture, and we
just can leave it out.

00:19:54.870 --> 00:19:57.080
Now, the boundaries
of the regions

00:19:57.080 --> 00:20:01.700
between soft and collinear here
seems like an interesting thing

00:20:01.700 --> 00:20:03.550
to worry about.

00:20:03.550 --> 00:20:07.400
And that is, indeed, true.

00:20:07.400 --> 00:20:09.470
You have to think about
how you want to set up

00:20:09.470 --> 00:20:11.060
this effective theory.

00:20:11.060 --> 00:20:13.425
And of course, as I have
been emphasizing earlier

00:20:13.425 --> 00:20:15.050
in the course, the
easiest way to think

00:20:15.050 --> 00:20:17.630
about momentum
degrees of freedom

00:20:17.630 --> 00:20:19.430
is with a Wilsonian picture.

00:20:19.430 --> 00:20:22.348
That makes physically
what's going on very clear.

00:20:22.348 --> 00:20:24.140
So the simplest thing
would be to introduce

00:20:24.140 --> 00:20:35.270
a Wilsonian cut-off
and set this up

00:20:35.270 --> 00:20:38.750
as a Wilsonian
effective field theory.

00:20:38.750 --> 00:20:40.910
And then we would just
take these regions.

00:20:40.910 --> 00:20:44.180
And I would literally carve
them out in the way that I drew.

00:20:44.180 --> 00:20:46.160
I would carve out some
cut-off between them.

00:20:46.160 --> 00:20:48.890
And I would decide who's
in the soft region, who's

00:20:48.890 --> 00:20:53.720
in the collinear region
based on those hard cut-offs.

00:20:53.720 --> 00:20:55.700
But we don't want to
do that, actually,

00:20:55.700 --> 00:20:59.240
because it would mess up
all sorts of symmetries.

00:20:59.240 --> 00:21:01.515
In particular, it would
mess up gauge cemetery

00:21:01.515 --> 00:21:03.140
which is an important
thing when you're

00:21:03.140 --> 00:21:05.400
talking about gauge theory.

00:21:05.400 --> 00:21:08.000
So we're going to use
dimensional regularization,

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:09.515
as we have for other problems.

00:21:29.360 --> 00:21:31.280
And that actually
will still leave us

00:21:31.280 --> 00:21:33.860
with this picture, which
I drew as a cartoon.

00:21:33.860 --> 00:21:35.000
You'll still be correct.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:37.400
Think about the modes
live in those places

00:21:37.400 --> 00:21:39.200
in dimensional regularization.

00:21:39.200 --> 00:21:42.020
What's a little bit harder is
how to think about the cut-off.

00:21:42.020 --> 00:21:46.121
And we'll treat that in
some detail later on.

00:21:46.121 --> 00:21:59.260
So it's still the
correct picture,

00:21:59.260 --> 00:22:04.740
but treating the region overlaps
with dimensional regularization

00:22:04.740 --> 00:22:05.740
is a little more tricky.

00:22:08.285 --> 00:22:09.910
But at least we can
do it in a way that

00:22:09.910 --> 00:22:11.692
preserves the gauge invariance.

00:22:17.050 --> 00:22:22.529
So that's going to be
our mode of operation.

00:22:43.500 --> 00:22:44.790
This theory has a name.

00:22:44.790 --> 00:22:48.020
It goes by the name SCET2.

00:22:48.020 --> 00:22:49.260
That's why I called it SCET2.

00:22:54.510 --> 00:22:59.780
We'll come back in a
moment to what SCET1 is.

00:22:59.780 --> 00:23:02.120
So I can say that the
degrees of freedom

00:23:02.120 --> 00:23:05.758
in this theory, the one that
we've been talking about,

00:23:05.758 --> 00:23:07.550
are some collinear
degree of freedom that's

00:23:07.550 --> 00:23:09.920
associated to some
direction, some collinear

00:23:09.920 --> 00:23:14.450
degrees of freedom as well as
some soft degrees of freedom.

00:23:14.450 --> 00:23:16.568
And when you have
effective theories that

00:23:16.568 --> 00:23:18.860
are like this one, where the
soft and collinear degrees

00:23:18.860 --> 00:23:21.230
of freedom live on the
same mass hyperbola,

00:23:21.230 --> 00:23:22.670
they're called SCET2 theories.

00:23:50.720 --> 00:23:53.090
And these are really
the kind of theories

00:23:53.090 --> 00:23:56.360
that you get when you're
talking about energetic hadron

00:23:56.360 --> 00:23:57.425
production.

00:24:09.820 --> 00:24:11.730
So any questions so far?

00:24:17.730 --> 00:24:21.420
OK, so if that's
energetic hadrons,

00:24:21.420 --> 00:24:23.520
then SCET1 will
be energetic jets.

00:24:23.520 --> 00:24:25.740
And that's what we'll
talk about next.

00:24:28.270 --> 00:24:31.950
So let's do another example
which has jets in it.

00:24:31.950 --> 00:24:34.530
And we'll see what
the similarities are

00:24:34.530 --> 00:24:39.690
to this SCET2 set up in terms
of just identifying still what

00:24:39.690 --> 00:24:43.630
the right degrees
of freedom are.

00:24:43.630 --> 00:24:45.810
So let's look at e plus
e minus to two jets.

00:24:53.730 --> 00:24:57.750
So e plus e minus collide.

00:24:57.750 --> 00:25:01.170
They produce a
virtual photon, say.

00:25:01.170 --> 00:25:05.250
The virtual photon produces
a quark-antiquark pair.

00:25:05.250 --> 00:25:08.430
The quark-antiquark
pair starts to radiate.

00:25:08.430 --> 00:25:12.690
And we get jets, two of them.

00:25:21.360 --> 00:25:23.243
So again, there's a
kind of natural frame

00:25:23.243 --> 00:25:24.410
to describe this scattering.

00:25:24.410 --> 00:25:28.460
And that's the center of mass
frame of the e plus e minus.

00:25:28.460 --> 00:25:30.860
Most e plus e minus colliders
are built in that frame.

00:25:37.120 --> 00:25:40.270
And if you're in the
center of mass frame

00:25:40.270 --> 00:25:44.530
and you call the for
momentum of this photon Q,

00:25:44.530 --> 00:25:47.650
then it just has an
energy component.

00:25:47.650 --> 00:25:50.320
So Q here is not the same as
the Q in our previous example,

00:25:50.320 --> 00:25:52.690
but we're always going to
identify the hard scale as Q.

00:25:52.690 --> 00:25:54.550
So here, the hard
scale is the scale

00:25:54.550 --> 00:25:58.823
of the energy of the collision
in the center of mass frame.

00:25:58.823 --> 00:26:00.490
And if you ask, what
does the event look

00:26:00.490 --> 00:26:02.080
like in the center
of mass frame,

00:26:02.080 --> 00:26:04.000
then these two jets
which are going out

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:05.480
have to balance each other.

00:26:05.480 --> 00:26:07.270
And so you have two
back to back jets.

00:26:10.300 --> 00:26:19.160
So we draw it like this, one jet
going this way, one jet going

00:26:19.160 --> 00:26:20.010
that way.

00:26:20.010 --> 00:26:21.890
Our original e plus e
minus might have come

00:26:21.890 --> 00:26:23.100
in from some other direction.

00:26:23.100 --> 00:26:29.030
So maybe e plus e minus were
coming in from here and here.

00:26:32.550 --> 00:26:36.440
And then we have these two
jets going out this way.

00:26:36.440 --> 00:26:38.690
Since they're jets,
that means they're

00:26:38.690 --> 00:26:40.460
collimated sprays of radiation.

00:26:46.745 --> 00:26:47.870
So they're not featureless.

00:26:47.870 --> 00:26:53.550
They have some size
to them like this.

00:26:53.550 --> 00:26:57.920
And in this process,
we can quickly

00:26:57.920 --> 00:27:00.560
identify that there's
two relevant directions.

00:27:00.560 --> 00:27:03.950
It's back to back,
but let's define

00:27:03.950 --> 00:27:07.460
this direction of
this jet to be n1,

00:27:07.460 --> 00:27:09.960
some lightlike vector that
points in that direction,

00:27:09.960 --> 00:27:11.870
and this one to be n2.

00:27:11.870 --> 00:27:16.940
So generically, we could
say you n is some 1, n hat.

00:27:16.940 --> 00:27:18.900
And if we choose this
to be the z-axis,

00:27:18.900 --> 00:27:24.120
then this must be 1, 0, 0
1, just like we had before.

00:27:24.120 --> 00:27:26.780
But we can always pick a
lightlike vector that points

00:27:26.780 --> 00:27:28.082
along some direction n hat.

00:27:28.082 --> 00:27:29.540
So when I draw a
picture like this,

00:27:29.540 --> 00:27:32.480
really what I mean when I say
n1 points in this direction

00:27:32.480 --> 00:27:35.360
is that the hat part of it
points in that direction

00:27:35.360 --> 00:27:38.520
in through space.

00:27:38.520 --> 00:27:41.160
OK, so just like
before, what happens

00:27:41.160 --> 00:27:44.040
with the jet is, as I
said last time actually,

00:27:44.040 --> 00:27:47.310
we have a large energy flow in
this direction and a smaller

00:27:47.310 --> 00:27:49.540
perpendicular flow.

00:27:49.540 --> 00:27:52.380
So if we measure
perpendicular momentum, which

00:27:52.380 --> 00:27:57.040
we can think of as perpendicular
to that axis, free axis,

00:27:57.040 --> 00:28:01.110
then that's the perpendicular
flow inside the jet.

00:28:01.110 --> 00:28:06.090
And so if we want to talk about
constituents inside the jet,

00:28:06.090 --> 00:28:08.670
then we'll be interested
in smaller perpendicular

00:28:08.670 --> 00:28:10.650
flow than flow in the
forward direction.

00:28:10.650 --> 00:28:13.960
And that's what makes it
into a collimated jet.

00:28:13.960 --> 00:28:14.710
You have question?

00:28:14.710 --> 00:28:15.390
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:28:15.390 --> 00:28:15.840
IAIN STEWART: Sure.

00:28:15.840 --> 00:28:17.423
AUDIENCE: So you're
not using anything

00:28:17.423 --> 00:28:19.440
about the QCD
[INAUDIBLE] to tell you

00:28:19.440 --> 00:28:20.828
the things is [INAUDIBLE].

00:28:20.828 --> 00:28:23.370
You're just saying we know that
we have to [INAUDIBLE] topic.

00:28:23.370 --> 00:28:25.740
IAIN STEWART: Yeah, that's
